rell in Wilts.","2  English: nickname, occupational name from Middle English  <i>chevrelle</i>, Old French  <i>chevrele</i>,  <i>chevrelle</i> ‘kid’ (before 1400,   OED  ), but in Middle English always used in the sense of  <i>cheverel leather</i> ‘kid leather’. The name may have been given to someone who wore kid leather or who sold articles made from it, as in the case of the Londoner below, whose different name forms prove that  <i>Cheverel</i> was sometimes a reduced form of  <i>Chevereller</i> ‘a maker or seller of kid-leather goods’. Compare Ralph le Cheverelmongere, 1310 in   London Letter Books   B."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":35,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary"